<h2>Word of the Day: "COMET" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown</h2>
<p><strong>Pronunciation:</strong> /'k?m?t/</p>
<p><strong>Part of Speech:</strong> Noun</p>
<p><strong>Definition(s):</strong></p>
<ol>
  <li>A celestial object consisting of a nucleus of ice and dust that, when passing close to the Sun, vaporizes and forms a glowing head and tail.</li>
  <li>Something that resembles a comet in its brilliance or speed.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Synonyms:</strong> meteor, shooting star, fireball</p>
<p><strong>Antonyms:</strong> planet, asteroid, star</p>
<p><strong>Example Sentences:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>The comet's tail was visible for weeks, a stunning sight in the night sky.</li>
  <li>The new employee was a real comet, shining brightly and making a big impact.</li>
  <li>The spacecraft was launched to study the comet's composition up close.</li>
  <li>Like a comet, the news of her promotion streaked across the office.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Etymology:</strong> From Old English "cometa," from Latin "cometa," from Greek "kometes," literally "long-haired," from "koma" "hair."</p>
<p><strong>Grammar Notes:</strong> "Comet" is a countable noun. It can be singular ("a comet") or plural ("comets").</p>

<h2>How I Solved Today's Wordle</h2>
<p>I started with "crane" to get some common vowels and consonants on the board. I was lucky to get the "C" right away, and the "E" turned yellow. My next guess, "table," confirmed the "E" was in the right spot and gave me a green "T".  "Stomp" helped me figure out the "M" wasn't in the word, and "comic" revealed the final "T" was also correct. </p>
<p>Feeling confident, I tried "comet" and voila! It was the right word. I was relieved to get it in five guesses today.</p>
<p>It was a satisfying solve, especially after yesterday's tricky one!</p>

<h2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle</h2>
<p>For a word like "comet," you want to start with words that cover a lot of common letters and vowel sounds. "Crane" is a great opener because it has a mix of vowels and consonants, including the tricky "R" which is often found in Wordle answers.</p>
<p>"Audio" is another strong choice. It uses different vowels than "crane" and includes the common letters "A," "U," and "O".</p>
<p>"Stare" is a good option because it has the vowels "A" and "E" which are frequently used in Wordle words. Plus, it includes the consonant "R" which is often found in the middle of words.</p>
<p>"Blitz" is a good choice because it uses some less common letters like "B," "L," and "Z" which can help you eliminate possibilities early on.</p>

<h2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns</h2>
<p>Today's answer, "comet," follows a slightly easier streak after the tricky "chump" and "afoot" from earlier this week. "Ivory" was also a bit challenging due to its unusual letter combination.</p>
<p>Interestingly, none of these recent answers share any letters with "comet," making it a bit of a curveball. It reminds us that Wordle can surprise us with words that don't follow obvious patterns.</p>
<p>While there's no clear pattern in recent answers, it's always good to keep in mind that Wordle likes to mix it up and challenge us with a variety of words!</p>

<h2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive</h2>
<p>One of the best ways to improve your Wordle game is to focus on letter frequency.  Letters like "E," "A," "R," "I," "O," and "T" are commonly used in English words, so starting with words that include these letters can be a smart strategy.</p>
<p>Don't be afraid to use word lists or online tools like the <a href="https://wordsolver.tech/wordle-solver">Wordle Solver tool</a> to help you brainstorm possibilities. These resources can give you ideas for words that fit the clues you've gathered so far.</p>
<p>Pay attention to word patterns. Wordle often uses words with common letter combinations like "TH," "SH," "CR," or "ST."  Keeping these patterns in mind can help you make more informed guesses.</p>
<p>Finally, don't get discouraged if you don't solve it in a few tries. Wordle is a game of strategy and deduction, and sometimes it takes a few guesses to get there. Keep trying, learn from your mistakes, and you'll improve your skills over time!</p>

<h2>Play Unlimited Wordle</h2>
