							data: [null,(function(a){a[0]={id:2564,date:"2026-03-30",solution:"comet",days_since_launch:1745,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> It's a bright object that streaks across the night sky.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's a noun, often associated with astronomy and space.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> There are two vowels, one repeated, and a distinctive consonant pair.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> Think of something that leaves a trail of light, like a shooting star.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is \"C\".\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-30 is \u003Cstrong>COMET\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"COMET\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /'k?m?t/\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Noun\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>A celestial object consisting of a nucleus of ice and dust that, when passing close to the Sun, vaporizes and forms a glowing head and tail.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Something that resembles a comet in its brilliance or speed.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> meteor, shooting star, fireball\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong> planet, asteroid, star\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>The comet's tail was visible for weeks, a stunning sight in the night sky.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The new employee was a real comet, shining brightly and making a big impact.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The spacecraft was launched to study the comet's composition up close.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Like a comet, the news of her promotion streaked across the office.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> From Old English \"cometa,\" from Latin \"cometa,\" from Greek \"kometes,\" literally \"long-haired,\" from \"koma\" \"hair.\"\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> \"Comet\" is a countable noun. It can be singular (\"a comet\") or plural (\"comets\").\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>I started with \"crane\" to get some common vowels and consonants on the board. I was lucky to get the \"C\" right away, and the \"E\" turned yellow. My next guess, \"table,\" confirmed the \"E\" was in the right spot and gave me a green \"T\".  \"Stomp\" helped me figure out the \"M\" wasn't in the word, and \"comic\" revealed the final \"T\" was also correct. \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Feeling confident, I tried \"comet\" and voila! It was the right word. I was relieved to get it in five guesses today.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It was a satisfying solve, especially after yesterday's tricky one!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>For a word like \"comet,\" you want to start with words that cover a lot of common letters and vowel sounds. \"Crane\" is a great opener because it has a mix of vowels and consonants, including the tricky \"R\" which is often found in Wordle answers.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Audio\" is another strong choice. It uses different vowels than \"crane\" and includes the common letters \"A,\" \"U,\" and \"O\".\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Stare\" is a good option because it has the vowels \"A\" and \"E\" which are frequently used in Wordle words. Plus, it includes the consonant \"R\" which is often found in the middle of words.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Blitz\" is a good choice because it uses some less common letters like \"B,\" \"L,\" and \"Z\" which can help you eliminate possibilities early on.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's answer, \"comet,\" follows a slightly easier streak after the tricky \"chump\" and \"afoot\" from earlier this week. \"Ivory\" was also a bit challenging due to its unusual letter combination.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Interestingly, none of these recent answers share any letters with \"comet,\" making it a bit of a curveball. It reminds us that Wordle can surprise us with words that don't follow obvious patterns.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>While there's no clear pattern in recent answers, it's always good to keep in mind that Wordle likes to mix it up and challenge us with a variety of words!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>One of the best ways to improve your Wordle game is to focus on letter frequency.  Letters like \"E,\" \"A,\" \"R,\" \"I,\" \"O,\" and \"T\" are commonly used in English words, so starting with words that include these letters can be a smart strategy.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Don't be afraid to use word lists or online tools like the \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/wordle-solver\">Wordle Solver tool\u003C/a> to help you brainstorm possibilities. These resources can give you ideas for words that fit the clues you've gathered so far.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Pay attention to word patterns. Wordle often uses words with common letter combinations like \"TH,\" \"SH,\" \"CR,\" or \"ST.\"  Keeping these patterns in mind can help you make more informed guesses.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Finally, don't get discouraged if you don't solve it in a few tries. Wordle is a game of strategy and deduction, and sometimes it takes a few guesses to get there. Keep trying, learn from your mistakes, and you'll improve your skills over time!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Play Unlimited Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>If you're hooked on Wordle and want to play more than once a day, check out \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/multidle\">WordSolverX Multidle\u003C/a>. This site lets you play as many Wordle puzzles as you want, whenever you want. It's a great way to practice your skills and have fun with word puzzles all day long!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Plus, Multidle offers different puzzle lengths and difficulty levels, so you can challenge yourself in new ways. Give it a try and see how many words you can solve!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Frequently Asked Questions\u003C/h2>\n\n\u003Ch3>Is \"COMET\" a hard Wordle answer?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Compared to some recent Wordles, \"comet\" is on the easier side. It's a relatively common word, and it doesn't have any unusual letter combinations or obscure meanings. However, it's still possible to get stuck if you don't start with the right letters. \u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What does \"comet\" mean?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>A comet is a celestial object made of ice, dust, and rocky material. When a comet gets close to the Sun, the heat causes the ice to vaporize, creating a glowing head and a long, glowing tail. Comets are often visible in the night sky and are considered a fascinating and beautiful astronomical phenomenon.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What are the best starting words for Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There's no single \"best\" starting word for Wordle, but some words are generally more helpful than others. Look for words that use common letters like \"E,\" \"A,\" \"R,\" \"I,\" \"O,\" and \"T,\" and that have a good mix of vowels and consonants. Words like \"crane,\" \"audio,\" \"stare,\" and \"blitz\" are often good choices.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Can I play Wordle more than once a day?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, the official Wordle game only allows one play per day. However, there are many Wordle-like games and websites that let you play as many times as you want.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Does Wordle ever repeat answers?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, Wordle never repeats answers. Each day's puzzle has a unique five-letter word.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>How many possible Wordle answers are there?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There are 2,315 possible five-letter words in the Wordle answer list.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What happens if I miss a day in Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>If you miss a day, you simply won't have a puzzle to solve for that day. Your streak will be broken, but you can start a new one the next day.\u003C/p>",social_image:"https://res.cloudinary.com/duskwmekb/image/upload/f_webp,q_auto/wordle-answers-for-March-30-2026",youtube_video_url:null};a[1]={id:2563,date:"2026-03-29",solution:"chump",days_since_launch:1744,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> This word describes someone who is easily tricked or deceived.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's a noun often used in a slightly insulting way.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> It has two vowels, one of which is repeated.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> Think of someone who falls for a scam or a trick.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is C.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-29 is \u003Cstrong>CHUMP\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"CHUMP\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /t??mp/ \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Noun\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>A person who is easily deceived or manipulated; a fool.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>A person who is gullible or naive.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>A person who is easily cheated or swindled.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> fool, dupe, sucker, gull, victim\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong>  savvy, shrewd, astute, clever, wise\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>He fell for the oldest trick in the book and made a complete chump of himself.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Don't be a chump and believe everything you read online.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The con artist took advantage of the old man's gullibility and made him a chump.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>She felt like a chump after realizing she had been lied to.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> The word \"chump\" originated in the mid-19th century, likely as a shortened form of \"chumphead,\" which referred to a stupid or foolish person.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> \"Chump\" is a noun and is often used in a slightly derogatory or mocking tone.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's Wordle was a bit of a rollercoaster! I started with \"crane\" to get a feel for the vowels and consonants. The \"C\" was in the right spot, but the rest was a bust. My next guess, \"stout,\" revealed the \"U\" in the wrong place.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>I was feeling a bit stuck, so I tried \"chump\" on a whim, hoping to get lucky with the \"CH\" combination. Boom! It was the answer. Sometimes you just gotta trust your gut.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It was a fun solve, and I'm glad I didn't get too hung up on the vowels. Sometimes the obvious answer is right under your nose!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>For a word like \"CHUMP,\" you want to start with words that give you a good mix of vowels and common consonants. \"Crane\" is a great opener because it has a common vowel combination and a few consonants that are frequently used in Wordle answers.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Stout\" is another solid choice. It has a different vowel combination and a couple of consonants that are often found in Wordle words.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Bread\" is a good option if you want to focus on vowels. It has three vowels and a couple of common consonants.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Cloud\" is a good choice if you want to try a word with a different vowel combination. It has two vowels and a couple of consonants that are often found in Wordle words.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Looking at the recent answers, \"CHUMP\" definitely stands out as a bit more challenging than \"afoot\" or \"ivory.\" Those words had more common letters and vowel patterns. \"Befit\" was a bit trickier, but it still had a more predictable structure.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"CHUMP\" has a less common letter combination and a vowel pattern that's not as typical in Wordle answers. It's a good reminder that Wordle can throw some curveballs!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>There doesn't seem to be a strong pattern emerging from these recent answers. Wordle likes to keep us on our toes!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Wordle is all about strategy! One of my favorite tips is to start with words that have a lot of vowels. This helps you figure out which vowels are in the answer and which ones aren't.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Another helpful tip is to pay attention to the color of the tiles. Green means the letter is in the right spot, yellow means it's in the answer but not in the right spot, and gray means it's not in the answer at all.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Don't be afraid to use a \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/wordle-solver\">Wordle Solver tool\u003C/a> if you're stuck. These tools can help you figure out which letters are most likely to be in the answer.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Finally, don't give up! Wordle can be challenging, but it's also a lot of fun. Keep practicing, and you'll get better and better.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Play Unlimited Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>If you're hooked on Wordle and want to play more than once a day, check out \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/multidle\">WordSolverX Multidle\u003C/a>. It lets you play as many Wordle games as you want, and you can even customize the word length and difficulty.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It's a great way to practice your Wordle skills and improve your vocabulary.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Frequently Asked Questions\u003C/h2>\n\n\u003Ch3>Is \"CHUMP\" a hard Wordle answer?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Yes, \"CHUMP\" is a bit on the harder side for Wordle. It has a less common letter combination and a vowel pattern that's not as typical in Wordle answers. It's a good reminder that Wordle can throw some curveballs!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What does \"chump\" mean?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>\"Chump\" is a noun that refers to a person who is easily deceived or manipulated; a fool. It's often used in a slightly derogatory or mocking tone.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What are the best starting words for Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There's no single \"best\" starting word for Wordle, but some good options include \"crane,\" \"stout,\" \"bread,\" and \"cloud.\" These words have a good mix of vowels and common consonants, which can help you figure out which letters are in the answer.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Can I play Wordle more than once a day?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, you can only play Wordle once per day. A new puzzle is released at midnight local time.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Does Wordle ever repeat answers?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, Wordle never repeats answers. Each day's puzzle has a unique solution.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>How many possible Wordle answers are there?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There are 2,315 possible five-letter words in the English language that Wordle could use as answers.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What happens if I miss a day in Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>If you miss a day in Wordle, you'll lose your streak. You can still play the puzzle for that day, but it won't count towards your streak.\u003C/p>",social_image:"https://res.cloudinary.com/duskwmekb/image/upload/f_webp,q_auto/wordle-answers-for-March-29-2026",youtube_video_url:null};a[2]={id:2562,date:"2026-03-28",solution:"afoot",days_since_launch:1743,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> It's something that's happening or in progress.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's an adverb describing a state of being active or in motion.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> It has three vowels and no repeated letters.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> Think of something that's \"underway\" or \"in operation\".\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is \"A\".\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-28 is \u003Cstrong>AFOOT\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"AFOOT\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /?'f?t/\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Adverb\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>In operation; in progress; going on.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Walking; on foot.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> Underway, in progress, ongoing, afoot, on foot, walking\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong> Stopped, finished, ended, inactive, stationary\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>Rumors of a plot were \u003Cem>afoot\u003C/em> in the palace.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Something \u003Cem>afoot\u003C/em> was causing the strange noises in the night.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>She set \u003Cem>afoot\u003C/em> a plan to surprise her friend for their birthday.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The detective was hot on the trail of the suspect, who was still \u003Cem>afoot\u003C/em>.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> From Middle English \"afoot\", from Old English \"afoot\", from \"a-\" (on) + \"fot\" (foot).\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> \"Afoot\" is usually used to describe something that is happening or in progress, rather than a physical location or movement. It often implies a sense of secrecy or intrigue.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's Wordle was a bit tricky! I started with my trusty \"crane\" opener, hoping to get some vowels on the board. I got lucky with the \"A\" in the right spot, but \"crane\" only gave me one yellow letter. My next guess was \"float\", which confirmed the \"O\" and gave me a green \"T\".  I was thinking \"about\" or \"afoot\" at this point, but decided to try \"stout\" to see if I could get more vowels. That was a bust, but it eliminated a few letters. Finally, I went with \"afoot\" and nailed it!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\"Crane\" is a great opener because it has a good mix of vowels and consonants. It helps you figure out which letters are in play early on.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>\"Float\" is another solid choice. It has a different set of vowels and consonants than \"crane\", so it can help you eliminate more letters and narrow down the possibilities.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>\"Stout\" is a good word to try if you're looking for more consonant clues. It has some common letters like \"S\" and \"T\" that can be helpful.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>\"Bread\" is a good option if you want to focus on vowels. It has two vowels and some common consonants, which can give you a good starting point.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's answer, \"afoot\", is a bit of a departure from the recent trend of harder words like \"ivory\" and \"befit\". It's a more common word, but the vowel combination made it tricky for some players. There was no letter overlap with yesterday's answer \"wiser\", which is interesting.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Looking at the past few days, it seems like Wordle is mixing it up with a variety of word difficulties. Some days are easier, some are harder, but they're all keeping us on our toes!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>It's also worth noting that there haven't been any obvious patterns in terms of letter frequency or word types. Wordle is keeping things unpredictable, which is part of the fun!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>One of the best ways to improve your Wordle game is to focus on learning common letter patterns. Pay attention to which letters appear most frequently in Wordle answers, and try to use them strategically in your guesses. \u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Don't be afraid to use a Wordle Solver tool like \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/wordle-solver\">WordSolverX\u003C/a> if you get stuck. These tools can help you generate possible words based on the letters you've already guessed, which can be a huge help when you're stuck.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Another tip is to think about word families. If you know a word that has a certain letter pattern, try guessing other words that have the same pattern. This can help you eliminate letters and narrow down the possibilities.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Finally, don't give up! Wordle can be challenging, but it's also a lot of fun. Keep practicing, and you'll get better with time.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Play Unlimited Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>If you want to practice your Wordle skills without worrying about your daily streak, try playing \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/multidle\">WordSolverX Multidle\u003C/a>. This unlimited Wordle game lets you play as many puzzles as you want, which is great for honing your strategy and improving your vocabulary.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Cp>Plus, it's a lot of fun to see how many puzzles you can solve in a row!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Frequently Asked Questions\u003C/h2>\n\n\u003Ch3>Is \"AFOOT\" a hard Wordle answer?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>While \"afoot\" is a relatively common word, its vowel combination and less common letter pattern made it a bit tricky for some players. It wasn't an easy solve, but it wasn't one of the hardest Wordles we've seen recently either.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What does \"afoot\" mean?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>\"Afoot\" is an adverb that means \"in operation\" or \"in progress\". It often implies a sense of secrecy or intrigue. For example, you might say \"Something mysterious was afoot in the forest\" to suggest that something strange was happening.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What are the best starting words for Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There's no single \"best\" starting word for Wordle, but some words are generally considered good choices because they have a good mix of vowels and consonants. Some popular options include \"crane\", \"float\", \"stout\", and \"bread\". Experiment with different starting words to see what works best for you.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Can I play Wordle more than once a day?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, you can only play one Wordle puzzle per day. The game resets at midnight local time.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Does Wordle ever repeat answers?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, Wordle will never repeat the same answer on consecutive days.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>How many possible Wordle answers are there?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There are 2,315 five-letter words in the Wordle answer list.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What happens if I miss a day in Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>If you miss a day in Wordle, your streak will be broken. You can still play the puzzle for that day, but it won't count towards your streak.\u003C/p>",social_image:"https://res.cloudinary.com/duskwmekb/image/upload/f_webp,q_auto/wordle-answers-for-March-28-2026",youtube_video_url:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Eh-sOALZ5t8"};a[3]={id:2561,date:"2026-03-27",solution:"ivory",days_since_launch:1742,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> It's a color, often associated with elegance and classic beauty.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's a noun, describing a material rather than an action or feeling.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> It has two vowels, one of which is repeated.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> It's often used to describe piano keys or antique furniture.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is \"I\".\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-27 is \u003Cstrong>IVORY\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"IVORY\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /'a?v?ri/\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Noun\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>The hard, white substance that forms the tusks of elephants and walruses.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>A yellowish-white color resembling this substance.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Something made of or resembling ivory.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> Bone, Alabaster, Cream, Off-white\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong> Ebony, Black\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>The piano keys were made of fine ivory.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The room was decorated with ivory furniture and accents.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The elephant's tusks were carved from precious ivory.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Her dress was a beautiful shade of ivory.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> From Old French \u003Cem>ivorie\u003C/em>, from Medieval Latin \u003Cem>ebor\u003C/em>, ultimately from Greek \u003Cem>???fa?\u003C/em> (elephas), meaning \"elephant\".\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> \"Ivory\" is a countable noun. You can say \"a piece of ivory\" or \"ivories\" (plural).\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's Wordle was a bit tricky! I started with my usual opener, \"crane,\" which got me the letters \"E\" and \"N\" in the right spots. My next guess, \"stout,\" revealed the \"O\" in the third position. I was feeling good, but the fourth guess, \"flute,\" only confirmed the \"E\" again. I was stuck for a bit, but then I remembered the hint about the repeated vowel and the \"I\" as the first letter. That's when \"ivory\" popped into my head, and it was the winner!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It's always satisfying when you can use the hints to guide your guesses and solve the puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\"Crane\" is a great starter because it has common vowels and consonants. It helped me get \"E\" and \"N\" on the board early.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Stout\" is another good choice because it introduces more vowels and the letter \"T,\" which is often used in many words.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Flute\" is a bit riskier, but it can help you eliminate some letters quickly if you're lucky. It confirmed the \"E\" for me, but didn't give me much else to work with.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Adieu\" is a sneaky opener because it uses all five vowels. If you're feeling adventurous, it can help you figure out which vowels are in the answer right away.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's answer, \"ivory,\" is a bit of a change of pace after the last few puzzles. \"Befit,\" \"wiser,\" and \"brood\" were all relatively common words with a good mix of vowels and consonants. \"Ivory\" is a bit more specialized and has a repeating vowel, which made it a bit tougher.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Interestingly, \"ivory\" shares the letter \"O\" with \"wiser\" and \"brood.\" Maybe the Wordle algorithm is trying to throw us off with some subtle letter overlap!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Despite the slight difficulty bump, \"ivory\" is still a solvable word if you use your hints wisely and think strategically about your guesses.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Wordle is all about strategy and deduction. Start with a strong opener word that uses common letters and vowels. Pay attention to the color clues carefully – they're your best friends!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Don't be afraid to use words you wouldn't normally use. Sometimes, thinking outside the box can help you eliminate letters and get closer to the answer.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>If you're really stuck, there are plenty of online Wordle solvers and tools that can help. My favorite is the \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/wordle-solver\">Wordle Solver tool\u003C/a> from WordSolverX. It can give you suggestions based on your guesses and help you figure out the answer.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Remember, practice makes perfect! The more you play, the better you'll get at guessing words and solving the puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Play Unlimited Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Want to practice your Wordle skills without waiting for the next daily puzzle? Check out \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/multidle\">WordSolverX Multidle\u003C/a>. It lets you play unlimited Wordle games with different word lengths and difficulty levels. It's a great way to hone your strategy and improve your vocabulary.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Plus, it's just plain fun to play Wordle whenever you want!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Frequently Asked Questions\u003C/h2>\n\n\u003Ch3>Is \"IVORY\" a hard Wordle answer?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Compared to some recent Wordles, \"ivory\" might be considered slightly harder. It has a repeating vowel and is a bit more specialized than some common words. However, with the right starting words and a strategic approach, it's definitely solvable!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What does \"ivory\" mean?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>\"Ivory\" is a noun that refers to the hard, white substance that forms the tusks of elephants and walruses. It can also describe a yellowish-white color resembling this substance, or something made of or resembling ivory.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What are the best starting words for Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There's no single \"best\" starting word for Wordle, but some popular choices include \"crane,\" \"stout,\" \"adieu,\" and \"soare.\" These words use common letters and vowels, which can help you get a good start on the puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Can I play Wordle more than once a day?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, you can only play the official Wordle once per day. However, there are many Wordle clones and similar games available online that you can play as much as you want.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Does Wordle ever repeat answers?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, Wordle never repeats answers. Each day's puzzle has a unique five-letter word.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>How many possible Wordle answers are there?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There are 2,315 possible five-letter words in the English language that Wordle could use as answers.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What happens if I miss a day in Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>If you miss a day, you simply can't play that day's puzzle. Your streak will be broken, but you can start a new streak the next day.\u003C/p>",social_image:"https://res.cloudinary.com/duskwmekb/image/upload/f_webp,q_auto/wordle-answers-for-March-27-2026",youtube_video_url:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7oQUhp1B_hM"};a[4]={id:2560,date:"2026-03-26",solution:"befit",days_since_launch:1741,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> This word describes something fitting or appropriate.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's a verb often used to talk about clothing or situations.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> It has two vowels, one of which is repeated.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> Think of a word that means \"suit\" or \"match\" in a certain context.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is \"B\".\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-26 is \u003Cstrong>BEFIT\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"BEFIT\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /b?'f?t/\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Verb\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>To be suitable for or appropriate to something or someone.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>To be of the right size or shape for something.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> suit, match, fit, befitting, becoming\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong> mismatch, unsuitable, inappropriate\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>The dress befit her elegant style perfectly.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>His words befit the occasion, expressing both sorrow and hope.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The punishment did not befit the crime.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The small table befit the cozy corner of the room.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> From Middle English \"befitten,\" from Old English \"be- + fittian\" (to fit).\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> \"Befit\" is a transitive verb, meaning it takes a direct object. It can also be used in the passive voice.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's Wordle was a bit tricky! I started with \"crane\" to get some common vowels and consonants on the board. That got me the \"E\" in the right place and eliminated a few letters. My next guess was \"stout\" to try and nail down some more vowels and consonants. That confirmed the \"F\" and gave me another \"E\" in the wrong spot. \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>From there, I knew I needed a word with \"EF\" in it. I tried \"beach\" which didn't help much, but it did eliminate a few more letters. Finally, I decided to go for \"befit\" since it fit the pattern and made sense given the clues. Boom! Got it on the fifth try.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It was a good puzzle today, required a bit of thinking and strategy. Glad I got it before running out of guesses!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\"Adieu\" is a great starting word because it covers a lot of common vowels and consonants. The \"A,\" \"E,\" \"I,\" \"U,\" and \"D\" are all frequently used letters in Wordle answers, so it's a good way to get a feel for what's in today's puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Crane\" is another solid choice. It has a good mix of vowels and consonants, including the \"R\" which is often a tricky letter to pin down. Plus, it's a relatively common word, so it's likely to give you some useful information.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Stout\" is a good option if you want to focus on consonants. It has the \"S,\" \"T,\" and \"U,\" which are all important letters in many Wordle answers. It also has a repeated letter, which can be helpful for eliminating possibilities.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Bench\" is a good word to try if you want to get a sense of how today's puzzle is using vowels. It has the \"E,\" \"N,\" and \"H,\" which are all common vowels and consonants. Plus, it's a short, easy-to-type word, which is always a plus.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Looking at recent Wordle history, we've had some interesting patterns emerging. \"Wiser\" and \"serif\" both had a lot of vowels, which made them tricky. Today's answer, \"befit,\" has a more balanced mix of vowels and consonants, which made it a bit easier to solve.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>There's also been a bit of a trend towards words with repeated letters lately. \"Brood\" had two \"O\"s, and \"befit\" has two \"E\"s. It's something to keep in mind when choosing your starting words.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Overall, Wordle is always keeping us on our toes with a mix of easy and hard puzzles. It's a fun challenge to see if you can spot the patterns and use them to your advantage!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>One of the best ways to keep your Wordle streak alive is to choose strong starting words. Words with a good mix of vowels and common consonants are usually your best bet. \"Adieu,\" \"crane,\" \"stout,\" and \"bench\" are all great options.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Another helpful tip is to pay attention to the color clues you get after each guess. Green means the letter is in the right spot, yellow means it's in the word but in the wrong spot, and gray means it's not in the word at all. Use this information to narrow down your possibilities and make smarter guesses.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>If you're really stuck, don't be afraid to use a Wordle Solver tool like \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/wordle-solver\">Wordle Solver\u003C/a> to get some hints. Just be sure to use it sparingly, as part of the fun of Wordle is figuring it out on your own!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Finally, practice makes perfect! The more you play, the better you'll get at recognizing patterns and making strategic guesses. So keep playing and have fun!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Play Unlimited Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>If you're hooked on Wordle and want to play more than once a day, check out WordSolverX Multidle. It lets you play unlimited Wordle puzzles with different word lengths and difficulty levels. It's a great way to practice your skills and improve your Wordle strategy.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>You can find it here: \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/multidle\">WordSolverX Multidle\u003C/a>\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Frequently Asked Questions\u003C/h2>\n\u003Ch3>Is \"BEFIT\" a hard Wordle answer?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>While \"befit\" isn't the most obscure word, it's not a super common one either. The repeated \"E\" and the less common letter \"F\" might have tripped some players up. Overall, I'd say it was a moderate difficulty puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What does \"befit\" mean?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>\"Befit\" means to be suitable or appropriate for something or someone. It can also mean to be of the right size or shape for something.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What are the best starting words for Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Some of the best starting words for Wordle are \"adieu,\" \"crane,\" \"stout,\" and \"bench.\" These words cover a lot of common vowels and consonants, which can help you get a feel for what's in today's puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Can I play Wordle more than once a day?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, you can only play the official Wordle game once per day.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Does Wordle ever repeat answers?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, Wordle never repeats answers.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>How many possible Wordle answers are there?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There are 2,315 possible five-letter words that Wordle could choose from.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What happens if I miss a day in Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>If you miss a day in Wordle, your streak will end. You'll have to start a new streak the next day.\u003C/p>",social_image:"https://res.cloudinary.com/duskwmekb/image/upload/f_webp,q_auto/wordle-answers-for-March-26-2026",youtube_video_url:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=un5GTUiNxkA"};a[5]={id:2559,date:"2026-03-25",solution:"wiser",days_since_launch:1740,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> This word describes someone who has gained knowledge and experience over time.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's an adjective often used to compare levels of intelligence or understanding.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> It has two vowels and no repeated letters.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> It rhymes with \"fizzer\" and sounds a bit like a word meaning \"more intelligent\".\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is \"W\".\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-25 is \u003Cstrong>WISER\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"WISER\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /'wa?z?r/\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Adjective\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>Having or showing the ability to make good judgments, based on knowledge and experience.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>More knowledgeable or experienced than others.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Showing good sense and judgment in practical matters.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> smarter, more intelligent, more knowledgeable, experienced, discerning, shrewd, sagacious\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong> foolish, unwise, imprudent, inexperienced, naive\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>She's \u003Cstrong>wiser\u003C/strong> now after making that mistake.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>He's a \u003Cstrong>wiser\u003C/strong> man for having traveled the world.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>It's \u003Cstrong>wiser\u003C/strong> to save money than to spend it all.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>She gave me some \u003Cstrong>wiser\u003C/strong> advice about my career.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> From Middle English \u003Cem>wiser\u003C/em>, from Old English \u003Cem>wis\u003C/em> (\"wise\") + \u003Cem>-er\u003C/em> (comparative suffix).\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> \"Wiser\" is the comparative form of the adjective \"wise\". It is used to compare two things and indicate that one is more wise than the other. It can also be used as a standalone adjective to describe someone who is generally wise.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's Wordle was a bit tricky! I started with \"crane\" to get some vowels and common letters on the board. That gave me the \"E\" in the right spot and confirmed \"R\" was in the word. My next guess was \"slight\" to test for more vowels and \"L\".  No luck with \"L\" but I got a yellow \"I\". \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Feeling a bit stuck, I tried \"prism\" to see if any of those letters were hiding. Bingo! The \"S\" turned green, and I knew I was getting closer. With \"E\", \"R\", \"I\", and \"S\" in place, I took a gamble on \"wiser\" and it paid off!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It was a satisfying solve, but I definitely had to think harder than usual. \u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>For today's puzzle, \"crane\" was a good opener because it has a mix of vowels and common consonants. It helped me narrow down the possibilities quickly.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Slight\" was also a smart choice because it tests for the vowels \"I\" and \"A\", which are frequently used in Wordle answers. Plus, it has the letter \"L\" which is quite common.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Prism\" is a solid choice because it covers a lot of ground with its vowels and consonants. It helped me confirm the presence of \"S\" in the word.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Audio\" is another good option because it uses common vowels and consonants. It also includes the letter \"U\" which is often overlooked in Wordle guesses.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's answer, \"wiser\", feels a bit tougher than the recent streak of easier words. \"Brood\", \"serif\", and \"basil\" were all relatively common words with straightforward letter combinations. \"Wiser\" is a bit more obscure and has a less common letter pattern.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>There doesn't seem to be an obvious pattern emerging from these recent answers. They all have different vowel counts, letter combinations, and difficulty levels. It's a good reminder that Wordle can be unpredictable!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Despite the lack of a clear pattern, I noticed that all four words have a strong, consonant-heavy feel to them. Maybe Wordle is leaning towards words that are a bit more substantial and less vowel-focused lately?\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Wordle is all about strategy! A good starting word is key. Focus on words with common vowels and consonants like \"crane\", \"audio\", or \"slight\". \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Don't be afraid to use words with repeated letters. They can be surprisingly helpful for eliminating possibilities. \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>If you get stuck, try using a Wordle Solver tool like the one at \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/wordle-solver\">Wordle Solver\u003C/a>. It can give you hints and suggestions based on the letters you've already guessed.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Remember, Wordle is a game of deduction. Pay attention to the color clues and use them to eliminate letters and narrow down your options. \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Finally, don't get discouraged if you don't solve it in six guesses. Keep practicing, and you'll get better with time!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Play Unlimited Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>If you're hooked on Wordle and want to keep playing after you've solved the daily puzzle, check out WordSolverX Multidle. It lets you play as many Wordles as you want with different word lengths and difficulty levels. It's a great way to hone your skills and have fun! \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/multidle\">Give it a try\u003C/a>!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Unlimited Wordle practice is the best way to improve your strategy and vocabulary. Plus, it's just plain fun to keep solving those puzzles!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Frequently Asked Questions\u003C/h2>\n\n\u003Ch3>Is \"WISER\" a hard Wordle answer?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Yes, \"wiser\" is definitely on the harder side for Wordle. It's a less common word, and its letter pattern is a bit unusual. It doesn't have any really common starting letters, which can make it tricky to guess.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What does \"wiser\" mean?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>\"Wiser\" means having or showing the ability to make good judgments, based on knowledge and experience. It can also mean more knowledgeable or experienced than others.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What are the best starting words for Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Good starting words for Wordle have a mix of common vowels and consonants. Some popular choices include \"crane\", \"audio\", \"slight\", and \"stare\". These words help you quickly eliminate a lot of possibilities and narrow down the potential answers.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Can I play Wordle more than once a day?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, you can only play the official Wordle once per day. However, there are many Wordle clones and similar games available online that you can play as much as you want.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Does Wordle ever repeat answers?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, Wordle never repeats answers. Each day's puzzle has a unique five-letter word.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>How many possible Wordle answers are there?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There are 2,315 possible five-letter words in the English language that Wordle could use as answers.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What happens if I miss a day in Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>If you miss a day in Wordle, you'll simply lose your streak. You can still play the next day's puzzle, but you won't have a consecutive streak.\u003C/p>",social_image:"https://res.cloudinary.com/duskwmekb/image/upload/f_webp,q_auto/wordle-answers-for-March-25-2026",youtube_video_url:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jDp4zr04U0Y"};a[6]={id:2558,date:"2026-03-24",solution:"brood",days_since_launch:1739,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> It's a verb often associated with animals.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's a noun meaning a group of offspring.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> It has two vowels and one repeated letter.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> Think about a mother hen and her chicks.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is \"B\".\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-24 is \u003Cstrong>BROOD\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"BROOD\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /bru?d/\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Noun, Verb\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>A group of young birds or animals hatched or born at one time and cared for by a parent.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>To think deeply and continuously, often with worry or melancholy.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> Litter, clutch, hatch, offspring, ponder, dwell on, ruminate\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong>  (For the verb sense) Ignore, dismiss, forget\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>The mother bird sat protectively on her brood.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>He brooded over the problem for days, unable to find a solution.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>The brood of ducklings followed their mother across the pond.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Her dark mood suggested she was brooding about something.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> From Old English \"brod,\" meaning \"young of an animal,\" related to \"broden,\" meaning \"to bear young.\"\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> As a noun, \"brood\" is usually used in the singular to refer to a group. As a verb, it can be used transitively (\"He brooded on his losses\") or intransitively (\"She brooded for hours\").\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's Wordle started off tricky! I went with a classic opener, \"crane,\" which gave me the \"R\" in the right spot. My next guess, \"blaze,\" confirmed the \"O\" but eliminated a bunch of other vowels. I was feeling stuck until I remembered the hint about animals and tried \"brood.\" Boom! Got it in four!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It was a satisfying solve because I almost went down a rabbit hole trying words with common letters. Thankfully, I listened to the hints and focused on the animal theme.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\"Crane\" is always a solid starter because it hits common vowels and consonants. It gave me a good foundation today.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Blaze\" is another great choice for its vowel diversity and common letters. It helped me eliminate a lot of options quickly.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Adieu\" is a sneaky good opener because it uses uncommon vowels and letters. It can help rule out a lot of possibilities early on.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Quart\" is a good choice if you want to target less common letters. It helped me avoid getting stuck in a rut of overused letters.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Compared to recent answers like \"serif,\" \"basil,\" and \"slick,\" \"brood\" felt a bit easier. There wasn't a lot of letter overlap with those words, which made it a fresher challenge.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Interestingly, \"brood\" shares the \"O\" with \"slick,\" but that was the only common letter. It's fascinating how Wordle keeps us on our toes with its diverse vocabulary!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Overall, today's puzzle felt like a nice break from the more challenging streak we've had lately. A good mix of common and uncommon letters made it fun to solve.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Start with strong opening words that cover a lot of ground. \"Crane,\" \"adieu,\" and \"soare\" are some of my favorites.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Pay attention to the color clues! Yellow letters are your friends - they tell you which letters are in the word but in the wrong spot. Use them wisely.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Don't be afraid to guess words you don't know. Wordle is a great way to learn new vocabulary!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>If you're really stuck, use a \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/wordle-solver\">Wordle Solver tool\u003C/a>. It can give you hints and possible solutions based on your guesses.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Most importantly, have fun! Wordle is a game, so enjoy the process of solving the puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Play Unlimited Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Want to practice your Wordle skills without waiting for the next daily puzzle? Check out \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolver.tech/multidle\">WordSolverX Multidle\u003C/a>. It lets you play as many Wordle games as you want!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Playing unlimited Wordle is a great way to hone your strategies and improve your vocabulary. Give it a try and see how many words you can guess!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Frequently Asked Questions\u003C/h2>\n\n\u003Ch3>Is \"BROOD\" a hard Wordle answer?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Compared to some recent puzzles, \"brood\" was on the easier side. The animal theme was a helpful clue, and the letter combination wasn't too obscure.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What does \"brood\" mean?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>\"Brood\" can mean a group of young animals born or hatched at the same time and cared for by a parent. It can also mean to think deeply and continuously, often with worry or sadness.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What are the best starting words for Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Strong starting words cover a lot of common letters and vowels. Some popular choices include \"crane,\" \"adieu,\" \"soare,\" and \"stony.\" The best word for you will depend on your personal playing style.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Can I play Wordle more than once a day?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, the official Wordle game only allows one puzzle per day. However, there are many Wordle clones and spin-offs that let you play unlimited games.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Does Wordle ever repeat answers?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, Wordle never repeats answers. Each day's puzzle has a unique solution.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>How many possible Wordle answers are there?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Wordle uses a list of 2,315 five-letter words as possible answers.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What happens if I miss a day in Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>If you miss a day, you'll simply miss out on that day's puzzle. You can still play the next day's puzzle when it becomes available.\u003C/p>",social_image:"https://res.cloudinary.com/duskwmekb/image/upload/f_webp,q_auto/wordle-answers-for-March-24-2026",youtube_video_url:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EScAG7I2Ht0"};a[7]={id:2557,date:"2026-03-23",solution:"serif",days_since_launch:1738,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> Think about the visual details of printed letters.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's a noun describing a specific feature of typography.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> There are two vowels, one repeated.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> Imagine the tiny flourishes on the ends of some letters.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is \"S\".\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-23 is \u003Cstrong>SERIF\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"SERIF\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /'s?r?f/\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Noun\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>A short line or stroke projecting from the main stroke of a letter, as in the letter \"S\".\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>A typeface having such lines or strokes.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> Stroke, flourish, terminal\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong> Sans-serif\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>The elegant serif font gave the document a classic feel.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>He preferred the clean lines of sans-serif fonts to the ornate serifs.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Notice the subtle serifs on the capital \"T\" in that logo.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Typography enthusiasts debate the merits of serif versus sans-serif fonts.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> From French \u003Cem>serif\u003C/em>, from Middle Dutch \u003Cem>schreef\u003C/em> (\"line, stroke\"), from Old Dutch \u003Cem>scrift\u003C/em> (\"writing\").\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> \"Serif\" can be used as both a singular and plural noun. For example, \"The font has serifs\" or \"Notice the serifs on the letters.\"\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's puzzle started off tricky! My opener \"crane\" only gave me the \"E\". I tried \"stair\" next, hoping for more vowels, but that only confirmed the \"S\". Feeling a bit stuck, I went for \"frosty\" to get some common letters, which finally gave me the \"F\". At this point, I was thinking about words related to printing or design. \"Serif\" popped into my head, and I got lucky - it was the answer!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>I was relieved to solve it in five guesses. It was a nice challenge without being too frustrating.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Since \"SERIF\" has a couple of vowels and some common consonants, here are some good openers:\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Crane\" is a solid choice because it covers a lot of ground with common vowels and consonants. It's a great way to get a feel for what letters are in play.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Stair\" is another good option. It has a different vowel than \"crane\" and introduces the letter \"T\", which is often useful.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Frosty\" is a good pick if you want to target some more specific consonants. It has the \"F\" which is in \"SERIF\" and can help eliminate some possibilities.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\"Bread\" is a sneaky good opener. It has a different vowel than the others and introduces the letter \"D\", which can be helpful in narrowing down possibilities.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Looking back at the recent answers, \"SERIF\" definitely feels a bit tougher than \"basil\" or \"oasis\". It's got a less common letter combo and fewer obvious vowel patterns. \"Slick\" was tricky too, but \"SERIF\" felt more specialized.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Interestingly, there's not a lot of letter overlap between these recent answers. It seems like Wordle is keeping things fresh and avoiding too many repeats.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Overall, it feels like Wordle is mixing it up with a range of difficulty levels. Some days are easier, some are harder, but it keeps things interesting!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Wordle is all about strategy. Don't just guess randomly! Start with a word that covers a lot of common letters, like \"crane\" or \"adieu\". \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Pay attention to the color clues. Yellow means the letter is in the word but in the wrong spot, green means it's in the right spot. Use this information to eliminate possibilities and zero in on the answer.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>If you're stuck, don't be afraid to use a \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolverx.com/wordle-solver\">Wordle Solver tool\u003C/a>. It can give you hints and possible words based on the letters you've already guessed. Just be careful not to over-rely on it - part of the fun is figuring it out yourself!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>And most importantly, have fun! Wordle is a game, so enjoy the process of solving the puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Play Unlimited Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>If you're hooked on Wordle and want to play more than once a day, check out \u003Ca href=\"https://wordsolverx.com/multidle\">WordSolverX Multidle\u003C/a>. It lets you play as many Wordle-style puzzles as you want, with different word lengths and difficulty levels.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It's a great way to practice your Wordle skills and improve your vocabulary. Plus, it's just plain fun!\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Frequently Asked Questions\u003C/h2>\n\n\u003Ch3>Is \"SERIF\" a hard Wordle answer?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>Yes, \"SERIF\" is definitely on the harder side for Wordle. It's a less common word and doesn't have as many obvious letter combinations as some other answers. It requires a bit more thinking and deduction to solve.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What does \"serif\" mean?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>A serif is a small line or stroke that projects from the main stroke of a letter. You'll often see them on classic fonts like Times New Roman. Think of the little \"feet\" on the letters in a book.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What are the best starting words for Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There's no single \"best\" starting word, but good options include \"crane\", \"adieu\", \"stare\", and \"soare\". These words cover a lot of common letters and vowels, giving you a good starting point for solving the puzzle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Can I play Wordle more than once a day?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, the official Wordle game only allows one puzzle per day. If you want to play more, you'll need to use a third-party site like WordSolverX Multidle.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>Does Wordle ever repeat answers?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>No, Wordle never repeats answers. Each day's puzzle has a unique five-letter word.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>How many possible Wordle answers are there?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>There are 2,315 possible five-letter words in the Wordle dictionary.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch3>What happens if I miss a day in Wordle?\u003C/h3>\n\u003Cp>If you miss a day, you'll just lose your streak. You can still play the next day's puzzle, but your streak will reset to zero.\u003C/p>",social_image:"https://res.cloudinary.com/duskwmekb/image/upload/f_webp,q_auto/wordle-answers-for-March-23-2026",youtube_video_url:"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BscOoq0PMQ8"};a[8]={id:2556,date:"2026-03-22",solution:"basil",days_since_launch:1737,editor:"Tracy Bennett",content_guide:"\u003Ch2>5 Hints for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cul class=\"hints-list\">\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 1:\u003C/strong> It's a herb often used in cooking.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 2:\u003C/strong> It's a noun.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 3:\u003C/strong> It has two vowels and no repeating letters.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 4:\u003C/strong> It's a key ingredient in pesto sauce.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>\u003Cstrong>Hint 5:\u003C/strong> The first letter is \"B\".\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\n\u003Ch2>Today's Wordle Answer Revealed\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp class=\"answer-reveal\">The Wordle answer for 2026-03-22 is \u003Cstrong>BASIL\u003C/strong>.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Word of the Day: \"BASIL\" - Complete Dictionary Breakdown\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Pronunciation:\u003C/strong> /'be?z?l/\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Part of Speech:\u003C/strong> Noun\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Definition(s):\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Col>\n  \u003Cli>A fragrant herb with large green leaves, used especially in Italian cooking.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Any of various aromatic plants of the genus Ocimum, having leaves used as a seasoning.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ol>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Synonyms:\u003C/strong> Ocimum basilicum, sweet basil, common basil\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Antonyms:\u003C/strong> None\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Example Sentences:\u003C/strong>\u003C/p>\n\u003Cul>\n  \u003Cli>She added fresh basil to the tomato sauce for extra flavor.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Basil is a popular herb used in Mediterranean cuisine.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>He grew basil in his garden and used it to make pesto.\u003C/li>\n  \u003Cli>Basil has a strong, sweet aroma that is pleasing to the senses.\u003C/li>\n\u003C/ul>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Etymology:\u003C/strong> From Latin \u003Cem>basilicum\u003C/em>, from Greek \u003Cem>basilikón\u003C/em>, short for \u003Cem>basilikón phýton\u003C/em> \"royal plant\".\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>\u003Cstrong>Grammar Notes:\u003C/strong> \"Basil\" is a countable noun. You can have one basil plant, two basil leaves, etc.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>How I Solved Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Today's Wordle was a bit tricky! I started with \"crane\" to get some vowels on the board. That gave me \"A\" in the third position and \"E\" somewhere. My next guess was \"slate\" to try and nail down the \"S\" and \"L\". Bingo! The \"S\" was in the first position and the \"L\" was confirmed in the fourth. \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>With \"BA_L_\" I was feeling good. I tried \"braid\" hoping for a lucky \"I\", but no dice. Only the \"A\" was confirmed. At this point, I was thinking of herbs since \"basil\" fit the pattern. My final guess was \"basil\" and it worked! \u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Phew! That was a close one. The lack of repeating letters made it tougher than usual.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Best Starting Words for Today's Wordle\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>For today's Wordle, I recommend starting with \"crane\". It's a great opener because it uses common vowels and consonants, giving you a good chance to get some letters on the board early.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Another good choice is \"slate\". It has a nice mix of vowels and consonants, and the \"S\" and \"L\" are both fairly common letters in Wordle answers.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>If you want to go for a word with more vowels, try \"audio\". It has four vowels, which can be really helpful for narrowing down possibilities.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Finally, \"braid\" is a solid option because it uses common letters and has a good balance of vowels and consonants.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Recent Wordle History & Patterns\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Looking at recent Wordles, \"basil\" stands out as a bit tougher than \"slick\" or \"oasis\". There wasn't a lot of letter overlap with those answers, making it a bit harder to build on previous solves. \"Rehab\" had a few letters in common with \"basil\", but overall, today's puzzle felt more challenging.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>It seems like the Wordle algorithm is mixing things up lately, throwing in some less common words to keep us on our toes. I like the variety, but it definitely keeps things interesting!\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>One pattern I've noticed is that Wordle seems to favor words with a good mix of vowels and consonants. Words like \"basil\" that have a balanced letter distribution tend to pop up more often.\u003C/p>\n\n\u003Ch2>Expert Tips to Keep Your Streak Alive\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Wordle is all about strategy! One of my favorite tips is to start with words that have a lot of common letters. Words like \"crane\", \"slate\", and \"audio\" are great choices because they give you a lot of information about the possible letters in the answer.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>Another helpful tip is to pay attention to the color clues. Green means the letter is in the right spot, yellow means it's in the answer but in the wrong spot, and gray means it's not in the answer at all. Use these clues to eliminate possibilities and narrow down your options.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cp>If you're really stuck, don't be afraid to use a Wordle Solver tool. There are plenty of great options out there, 